#coda-heading("The Deep End — New Connections and Old Ancestors")

#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", font: "Optima", fill: luma(110))[
  None of what follows is required reading. The booklet was the booklet. The conclusion was the conclusion. What follows is for whoever wants to stay at the table for one more drink — a few connections between NVC and a handful of older and newer pieces of work that nobody seems to be making in print, and that the author keeps thinking about. Skip it freely. Pick at it. Read the parts that interest you. Close the booklet at any point.
]

#v(1em)

*The magic claim, once more, in slightly stronger form.*

NVC is not, structurally, a communication technique. It is a piece of working magic.

By _magic_ we do not mean the woo. We mean the older, operative sense — what Alan Moore is doing when he points out that to cast a spell is simply to spell, to manipulate words, to change people's consciousness, and that _a grimoire is just a grammar._ What Robert Anton Wilson is doing when he calls the verb _to be_ a _deity mode of speech._ What Wittgenstein meant when he described philosophy as a battle against the bewitchment of our intelligence by means of language. Some sentences do not describe the world; they enact something in it. They marry. They convict. They bless. They curse. _I now pronounce you_ is not a description of the event. It is the event.

Consider the basic move of NVC, then.

_You are selfish_ renders Elizabeth permanently. It uses the deity mode of speech: it places a permanent quality onto a person, in a moment, by an authority — yours — and the only response available is contestation. Either Elizabeth accepts your verdict and reorganizes herself around your judgment, or she defends, and you escalate, and the verdict gets sharper with each exchange.

_You didn't text me back for two days, and I am hurt, and I am longing for partnership_ does not render Elizabeth at all. It reports an event that happened in a body, in a moment, for a reason. There is no permanence claim. There is no verdict. The other person can meet the longing or not, but they cannot be made permanent by the sentence. They are not on trial. They are being met.

The same grammar holds when you are the one who has been harmed. _He is an abuser_ is the is-of-identity aimed in a direction that feels righteous — it might even feel accurate — but it works by the same mechanism. It renders a person permanent by their worst behavior. Harm describes behavior. Behavior can be named, accounted for, sometimes changed. The person is not the act, even when the act has been serious and the pattern long.

Naming the pattern accurately leaves more room for actual accountability than naming a person evil ever does. Including, sometimes, yourself — the version of you who did something you cannot forgive, who you have been rendering permanent ever since.

This is the claim. The rest of this postscript is the receipts.

#divider

*Your brain is not a bucket for emotions.*

#pullquote[Your brain is not a bucket for emotions. It is a prediction machine.]

The standard model — the one most of us were raised inside, even those of us who never thought about it — runs roughly like this. There are emotions in the world. You have them. They appear when something happens. They are basic, universal, hardwired. You feel angry the way you feel hungry. Trigger arrives, affect program fires, experience is delivered. Done.

This is, on inspection, mostly wrong. The neuroscientist Lisa Feldman Barrett has spent the past two decades demonstrating that emotions are not retrieved from a bucket. They are constructed, in real time, by a brain whose primary job is to predict. The brain takes the body's interoceptive signals — chest tightness, gut weight, heat in the face — and combines them with two other ingredients. Past experience: what does this body-state usually mean for me. And concepts: what categories does my language give me to make sense of it.

The third ingredient is the load-bearing one. The emotion concepts you have available are the categories your brain reaches for when it is constructing what you are feeling. The brain does not pre-feel the emotion and then look for the word. It uses the word — the concept, the granularity available in your vocabulary — to assemble the emotion in the first place.

Barrett calls this _emotional granularity._ The finding, repeated across studies, is uncomfortably blunt. People with finer-grained vocabulary do not just describe their feelings differently. They have different feelings. The person who can distinguish between hurt, betrayed, rejected, dismissed, and lonely is not running four labels over a single underlying state. They are constructing four states, each with different implications for action, different physiological signatures, different downstream consequences for what the body and the relationship do next. Coarse vocabulary, coarse experience. Precise vocabulary, precise experience.

This is not metaphor. The brains have been measured.

Read NVC's insistence on a real feelings vocabulary in light of this and the practice stops looking like a stylistic preference. _I feel attacked_ is, by inspection, an evaluation in feeling-clothing — a story about what someone else is doing to me — and saying it constructs an emotional state organized around being-attacked. The body locates it. The threat program runs. The sentence becomes the experience. _I feel hurt and longing to matter_ is a different concept. It is a different construction, in a different part of the body, organized around an unmet longing rather than an incoming weapon. Same Tuesday, same kitchen, same partner. Different sentence. Different feeling. Not because the speaker has reframed a thing they were already feeling. Because the sentence built a different thing.

This is the move underneath the entire feelings/needs vocabulary in the practice — the reason Rosenberg's lists run so long, the reason the chart you printed and taped to the fridge actually does anything once it is up there. The vocabulary is not for getting better at describing what was already there. It is the toolkit that decides what gets there in the first place.

It is also why the pseudo-feelings — _I feel attacked, dismissed, used, abandoned, manipulated_ — are not just imprecise. They are constructions of being-acted-upon, dressed in feeling-clothing. Saying them out loud installs a particular kind of person, in a particular kind of state, in the room. The other person, often correctly, hears the verdict instead of the feeling and defends. The construction has already done its work before anyone has decided to fight.

A small fairness note. Barrett's view is contested in some quarters; the literature has its own internal arguments. But the core finding — that emotion concepts shape emotional experience, that vocabulary changes states — has been replicated across enough domains and enough labs to be load-bearing. NVC's practice was developed without any of this in view. The convergence is striking. Marshall Rosenberg appears to have noticed the mechanism by sitting in enough difficult rooms; Barrett confirmed it with fMRI and several thousand participants. They are pointing at the same fact.

#divider

*The body reads the sentence before the mind does.*

That covers what is happening inside one head. The other half of the magic is what is happening between two heads in the same room.

Stephen Porges' polyvagal theory describes the autonomic nervous system as running in three states, not two. The familiar pair — fight-or-flight (sympathetic) and rest-and-digest (parasympathetic) — turns out to be too coarse. Porges argues for three: ventral vagal (social engagement, calm, connection, safe), sympathetic (mobilized, prosecutorial, ready to fight, scared), and dorsal vagal (shutdown, freeze, gone underwater, numb). Most of what we have been calling _calm_ lives in the ventral vagal state. Most of what we have been calling _out of it_ lives in dorsal. The middle one — the activated, fighty, certain state — is the one most fights actually happen from.

The other concept that does the work is _neuroception._ Below the threshold of conscious processing, the nervous system is constantly scanning the environment for cues of safety or threat. Tone of voice. Facial micro-expression. Body posture. The shape of the room. Whether the other person's body has decided they are safe or not. Whether the words coming out match the body delivering them. The threat-scan does not wait for the language centers to process the sentence. It has already decided, and acted, before the cortex finishes parsing.

This is where the Barrett story extends into the room. The grammar of moralistic verdict — _you are selfish, he is an abuser, you always do this_ — functions, regardless of speaker tone, as a neuroceptive cue of threat. The listener's body reads it as attack. The sympathetic system goes online. The room's nervous-system temperature rises before anyone has chosen to fight. The defense is up. The conversation is, in a meaningful sense, already over.

The grammar of NVC — vulnerable, located in the body, requesting rather than demanding, no permanent verdict on anyone — functions as a cue of safety. The listener's nervous system reads it as not-attack. The ventral vagal system stays online, or comes back online if it had already started to mobilize. The social-engagement system stays available, which is the only state in which conversation between two adults is actually possible.

This is also why the dead-eyed-therapist-demo voice does not produce the effect. Perfect NVC sentences delivered by a body that is itself in sympathetic activation, performing helpfulness from inside its own dysregulation — the form is right; the signal is wrong. The other body's neuroception has already clocked the mismatch and gone defensive. Words alone do not regulate a nervous system. Bodies regulate nervous systems. The words help when the body is also doing the work.

Co-regulation is the lived consequence. Two bodies in a room. One of them in distress — wired hot or gone numb. The other regulated, present, not in a hurry, signaling safety with everything it is broadcasting beneath language. The regulated body offers, to the dysregulated body, the cues of safety the dysregulated body cannot manufacture alone. Slow voice. Soft eyes. Steady breath. Unhurried timing. The other body's nervous system, given enough of those cues for long enough, comes back online.

This is the half of empathic listening the textbook skips. The empathy is doing nervous-system work, not just communication work. It is regulating the room from underneath. Half the conversation is happening below the words, in the shared space the bodies are in together.

A note on the science. Polyvagal theory has its critics, and some of the more sweeping claims in the popular literature outrun the data. The three-state model and neuroception, however, are robust enough and useful enough to be worth knowing. They give us a precise account of why the same information delivered in two different grammars produces two different rooms.

Put the Barrett move and the Porges move together and the chain runs end to end. Precise feeling-vocabulary constructs different emotional states. Those states broadcast different neuroceptive signals. The listener's body responds to the signal before the conscious mind processes the words. NVC is doing physiological work. The grammar is, in the most literal sense, changing the bodies in the room.

#divider

*Grammar as grimoire.*

The neuroscientists, in other words, are working hard to recover an insight that has, in other vocabularies, been around for several thousand years.

The word _grammar_ and the word _glamour_ derive from the same root. Old French _gramaire_ — Latin learning, grammar, and, by extension, the kind of arcane knowledge associated with monkish learning, which slid in Scottish English into _glamour_ as enchantment, spell, the thing that makes a person see what is not there. Grammar is glamour. The two words are siblings. Moore was not being cute when he said a grimoire is just a grammar. He was being etymological.

The Hebrew _dabar_ — usually translated as _word_ — does not separate the speech-act from the deed. The divine word is not the description of creation; it is the act. _And God said, let there be light, and there was light._ The word and the thing named are not in a relationship of description. The naming is the making. The deed and the word are one act; the sentence is the event. This is not theological metaphor. It is the literal structure of the text, and the traditions that built on it — many of them, across centuries, starting from different premises — arrived at variations of the same point. Words do something. They are not descriptions of the world; they are part of how the world keeps assembling itself, moment to moment.

NVC's claim — that the sentence does not narrate the speaker but builds the speaker; that the moralistic verdict makes a particular kind of room, and the precise feeling-and-need makes a different kind of room — is not a new claim. It is a very old claim, recovered in the language of contemporary neuroscience.

#divider

*Korzybski's quiet century.*

The more recent recovery, closer to the surface, runs through a strange lineage — Korzybski, Bourland, Wilson — three men with an unfortunate amount of overlap with the kind of internet that talks too much about the Illuminati, and one genuinely useful set of ideas underneath.

Alfred Korzybski's _Science and Sanity_, published in 1933, is unreadable. The insight is not. He spent eight hundred dense pages arguing that the verb _to be_ — specifically the _is of identity_, the _John is a fool_ and _she is selfish_ shape — installs a kind of false certainty into ordinary speech, treating contingent observations as permanent essences. The map, Korzybski insisted, is not the territory. The word is not the thing. _Whatever you say a thing is, it is not._ The sentence shape that places permanent identities onto people and objects, he argued, is doing something specific to the speaker's cognition: installing a flattened, essentialized model of a world that is in fact dynamic, contextual, and nobody's fixed possession.

D. David Bourland Jr., his student, took the move further into the practical. In the 1960s he proposed _E-Prime_ — English without _to be_. Not banned forever; banned as an experiment, to see what speech sounded like when one was no longer permitted to render anyone or anything permanent. The result is exactly what NVC's grammar produces, by a different route. _He is selfish_ has no E-Prime translation. You have to say what he did, when, and how it landed in you. The is-of-identity dissolves; the body and the moment return.

Robert Anton Wilson, who picked up the thread from both of them and ran it into the broader counterculture, gave the move its sharpest popular framing. Each of us, he argued, lives inside a _reality tunnel_ — a perceptual world constructed by our nervous system, our language, and our beliefs. Everyone's tunnel is partial. Everyone's tunnel feels like the whole world from inside. Most of what humans call disagreement is two reality tunnels colliding, each certain it is just describing the way things are. The way out of the trap is not finding the one true tunnel. It is holding one's own tunnel more lightly — saying _it seems to me_ instead of _it is_, treating one's perceptions as hypotheses rather than verdicts.

This is the epistemological mood NVC's grammar produces, by another mechanism. The speaker who cannot render anyone permanent in a sentence is the speaker who has stopped pretending their tunnel is the only one in the room. Marshall Rosenberg appears to have arrived at the same conclusion without going through general semantics; the resemblance is striking enough that the comparative essay should one day be written.

#divider

*A game you cannot win inside the old house rules.*

There is one more handle, and it comes from a philosopher who would have hated everything about the last three paragraphs.

#pullquote[Wittgenstein said language is not a description of reality but a collection of games you play. NVC is a game you cannot win inside the old house rules.]

That sentence is the entire pedagogical move. It is also the answer to the most common reasonable objection skeptics raise about the practice, which is: this stuff sounds completely fake when I try it.

The skepticism is correct. It does sound fake. It sounds like cosplay, and not just on day one — sometimes on day five hundred, in the kitchen, when you are exhausted and your partner has done the dishes-thing again and you are trying to come up with _I'm feeling X and I'm needing Y_ as if you were reading from an index card. Of course it sounds fake. You are trying to play a new language game inside the old form of life.

Wittgenstein's late work — the _Philosophical Investigations_, published after his death in 1953 — argued that language does not have a single essence. It is not, as he had once thought, a picture of reality. It is a collection of practices, each embedded in what he called a _form of life_: the broader pattern of activities, relationships, and shared assumptions inside which the words make any sense at all. A _language game_ is not a metaphor. It is a complete practice, words and all, running inside a particular form of life.

Different forms of life run different language games. The language game of the courtroom does not work in the kitchen. The language game of a quarterly performance review does not work between two people in love. The language game of the teenage friend group does not work at the funeral. Try to use one inside the other and the result, predictably, is dissonance — the words are right; the form of life is wrong; everyone in the room hears the mismatch.

This is what is happening every time someone tries to drop OFNR into a marriage still running on domination culture, or a workplace still running on hierarchy and performance, or a family still running on the older language game of moralistic blame. The form of life has not changed. The language game is being parachuted in. Of course it sounds fake. The kitchen does not change just because you learned a new sentence.

What is required, if NVC is to stop sounding rehearsed, is not better delivery of the new language game inside the old form of life. It is a slow change in the form of life itself. The relationships have to be reorganized around the practice. The assumptions about who has authority, and what authority is, have to shift. The shared vocabulary of feelings and needs has to actually become shared, not just spoken at, by one person reading from the card. The new form of life arrives slowly, badly, by accumulation. One day the new sentences stop sounding rehearsed because the form of life has, by then, partly arrived.

Wittgenstein, in another moment, said that the goal of philosophy was a battle against the bewitchment of our intelligence by means of language. He meant that some of our most stubborn confusions are not factual errors but grammatical ones — knots that look like deep philosophical problems but are actually problems with how the language we are speaking has constructed the question.

_He is selfish_ is one of those knots. The grammar bewitches us into thinking we are describing a fact when we are constructing a verdict. The whole NVC practice, read in this light, is therapeutic philosophy in the Wittgensteinian sense. Not the building of a better theory. The dissolution of a confusion. Showing the fly the way out of the fly-bottle it has been knocking against for years.

#cross-break

*The anarchist sentence.*

Underneath all of this, in Rosenberg's own pages and not in the workshop pamphlets, is a sharper claim than the practice's reputation suggests.

From the second chapter of _Nonviolent Communication: A Language of Life:_

#blockquote[
  Life-alienating communication both stems from and supports hierarchical or domination societies, where large populations are controlled by a small number of individuals to those individuals' own benefit... The language of wrongness, should, and have to is perfectly suited for this purpose: the more people are trained to think in terms of moralistic judgments that imply wrongness and badness, the more they are being trained to look outside themselves — to outside authorities — for the definition of what constitutes right, wrong, good, and bad. When we are in contact with our feelings and needs, we humans no longer make good slaves and underlings.
]

That is not a self-help sentence. That is structurally an anarchist sentence. It identifies the language of moral judgment as the linguistic substrate of obedience. It identifies the practice of locating one's own feelings and needs as a refusal of that obedience. _When we are in contact with our feelings and needs, we humans no longer make good slaves and underlings._ Read it twice. Rosenberg, in his quietly sweatered way, is making a frankly political claim about what the moralistic-blame language game is for. It is for keeping populations governable.

It is worth naming because the field tends to pretend Rosenberg did not write it.

The political dimension also explains why some of the most interesting work being done with NVC in the world is happening at the intersection with restorative justice, anarchist mediation, and prefigurative organizing — and why those threads tend to get softened in standard introductions.

Dominic Barter developed _Restorative Circles_ in the favelas of Rio de Janeiro starting in the late 1990s, working initially with at-risk youth and the conflicts that ran through their communities. He was not designing a workshop product. He was designing a community-held process that could replace the state and the expert as the authority structures around conflict — that could put a community in a circle, give it the language and the procedure to face what had happened, and let it do the work without anyone outside that room being in charge. The structural innovation is unmistakable. The circle replaces the courtroom. The community replaces the judge. The language of feelings and needs replaces the language of guilt and punishment. NVC, scaled up and structurally non-state.

Barter's work has spread to dozens of countries — schools, prisons, post-conflict community mediation. It is, by inspection, a piece of prefigurative political practice: building the institutions of a post-state society inside the existing one. That this branch of NVC tends to be invisible in the introductory literature is itself a fact worth noticing.

Miki Kashtan's consensus and convergent-facilitation work runs along similar lines, providing decision-making structures for groups that do not want to run on majority-vote or hierarchical command. Roxy Manning, Edmundo Norte, and Meenadchi have spent years arguing that NVC's standard packaging — the white middle-class workshop format, the assumption of bodies that have not been racialized into chronic survival mode, the expectation of emotional disclosure in a particular register — re-installs the dominator culture it was meant to refuse, and that the practice has to be retooled to do its actual political work in the bodies it was not originally designed for. None of this is fringe. It is the part of NVC the standard pamphlets soften, because the standard pamphlets are sold to corporations.

The deeper claim, when read seriously, is about sovereignty. NVC's deepest commitment is the proposition that nobody — including you — has the authority to render anyone else permanent. The sentences that render permanently are the sentences that make people governable. The sentences that locate feelings and needs without rendering anyone permanent are the sentences that produce sovereign people. _Connection over control_ is the slogan. The substance underneath the slogan is anarchist in the precise structural sense. Stories about people are stories. The person is still the person. They are allowed to surprise you. They are allowed, even, to surprise themselves.

The same goes for you. The story you have been telling yourself about yourself for the past twenty years is also a story. The internal courtroom is also an institution. You can decline its jurisdiction.

#divider

*No-self, and the dishes.*

The newest of these traditions is a hundred and fifty years old. The oldest is older than that by an order of magnitude.

The Buddhist concept of _anatman_ — non-self, no-self, the absence of a fixed permanent essence — is the ancient form of the same insight. The teaching is not, as it sometimes gets translated, that there is no person there. The teaching is that the person is not a fixed thing. The self is a moving collection of perceptions, sensations, mental formations, and habits — a process, not a possession. The "permanent quality" we keep trying to render onto people in our sentences was never there to be rendered.

Two and a half thousand years later, the philosopher Nagarjuna — second-century Indian Mahāyāna — gave the move its sharpest articulation. His Madhyamaka philosophy turns on the doctrine of two truths: _saṃvṛti satya_, conventional or relative truth, and _paramārtha satya_, ultimate truth. At the conventional level, things have names, behaviors can be described, agreements can be made, harm can be accounted for. At the ultimate level, no thing has a fixed essence — everything depends, arises in relation, has no standalone selfhood that could be permanently rendered by a sentence.

The two truths are not in competition. They are layers. We need conventional truth to live — to call you by your name, to ask the dishes question, to name a pattern of behavior accurately and ask for it to change. We also need ultimate truth, in the background, to keep us from mistaking the conventional names for permanent essences. _He keeps not doing the dishes, and I am exhausted, and I am longing for partnership_ is conventional truth, accurately spoken. _He is selfish_ is conventional truth that has forgotten there is an ultimate level — a sentence that has hardened into a verdict pretending to be a description.

NVC is, in this light, doing Madhyamaka in everyday English. It is keeping the speaker honest about the difference between behavior described and essence claimed. It does this without ever asking the speaker to think about Madhyamaka, which is why it works for people who would never read Nagarjuna and would gain nothing by being told they were doing his work for him. The practice is the practice. The philosophical lineage is interesting if you happen to find it interesting. The dishes still need to be done either way.

There is, by now, a long list of practices and traditions that have, by their own routes, arrived at the same place. The unitary, fixed, judging self pronouncing on the world from a permanent throne is not what is actually here, and the language we speak inside that misunderstanding produces most of our suffering. NVC is one such practice. So is Internal Family Systems. So is somatic trauma work. So are the better corners of the dharma traditions. So is, in its own register, the working magic of the grimoire-grammar tradition. They are pointing at the same fact, in different rooms, with different instruments. The fact is the fact.

#divider

*A hinge between rooms.*

That is, finally, what we mean when we say NVC is a hinge.

It is not a tradition unto itself. It is not the room. It is a door between rooms — between Internal Family Systems and codependence recovery, between somatic trauma work and anarchist mediation, between Korzybski's general semantics and the dharma traditions that have been pointing at the same thing for two and a half thousand years. Most of the practice's actual value, lived inside, is in this translator role. A small portable grammar that lets traditions which would otherwise have nothing to say to each other recognize that they are pointing at the same fact.

The people who have hardened NVC into a primary identity have mostly missed what makes it worth doing. The people who hold it lightly, and use it as a tool inside a larger life, tend to do better with it.

